  "prompt": "What are some of the best Soft Rock songs of all time?",
  "response": "Ah, soft rock! The genre that's perfect for mellowing out, road trips, or just enjoying a chill vibe. Defining \"best\" is always subjective, but here's a list of some of the most popular, enduring, and critically acclaimed soft rock songs of all time, spanning different eras and subgenres within soft rock:\n\n**Classics & Staples:**\n\n*   **\"Your Song\" - Elton John (1970):**  A piano-driven ballad with heartfelt lyrics, this is quintessential early soft rock.\n*   **\"You've Got a Friend\" - Carole King (1971):**  A song about unwavering support and friendship, it's a timeless classic.\n*   **\"Killing Me Softly With His Song\" - Roberta Flack (1973):**  A smooth, soulful, and deeply emotional masterpiece.\n*   **\"Dust in the Wind\" - Kansas (1977):**  A philosophical and melancholic acoustic-driven song.\n*   **\"Wonderful Tonight\" - Eric Clapton (1977):**  A simple, romantic, and beautifully understated love song.\n*   **\"Three Times a Lady\" - Commodores (1978):** A soulful ode to the women in our lives.\n*   **\"Against the Wind\" - Bob Seger (1980):** A nostalgic and reflective song about growing older.\n*   **\"Arthur's Theme (Best That You Can Do)\" - Christopher Cross (1981):** Smooth, sophisticated, and Oscar-winning.\n\n**70s Soft Rock Gems:**\n\n*   **\"Brandy (You're a Fine Girl)\" - Looking Glass (1972):**  A nautical-themed, catchy, and slightly bittersweet song.\n*   **\"Crazy Love\" - Van Morrison (1970):**  Soulful, romantic, and effortlessly cool.\n*   **\"Daniel\" - Elton John (1973):** A poignant and mysterious ballad.\n*   **\"The Way We Were\" - Barbra Streisand (1973):**  A nostalgic and emotional ballad from the film of the same name.\n*   **\"I'm Not in Love\" - 10cc (1975):**  Atmospheric, layered, and incredibly unique for its time.\n*   **\"Summer Breeze\" - Seals and Crofts (1972):**  A breezy, folk-infused song that perfectly captures the feeling of summer.\n*   **\"Lyin' Eyes\" - Eagles (1975):**  Storytelling at its finest, with beautiful harmonies.\n*   **\"After the Gold Rush\" - Neil Young (1972):**  A beautifully haunting and eco-conscious song.\n\n**80s Soft Rock & Adult Contemporary:**\n\n*   **\"The Lady in Red\" - Chris de Burgh (1986):**  A romantic and iconic ballad.\n*   **\"Take My Breath Away\" - Berlin (1986):**  From the *Top Gun* soundtrack, a powerful and soaring love song.\n*   **\"Careless Whisper\" - George Michael (1984):**  Smooth, sensual, and instantly recognizable.\n*   **\"Eternal Flame\" - The Bangles (1988):**  A sweet and melodic ballad.\n*   **\"Right Here Waiting\" - Richard Marx (1989):**  A heartfelt and emotional power ballad.\n*   **\"Saving All My Love for You\" - Whitney Houston (1985):**  A powerful and emotional ballad showcasing Houston's incredible vocals.\n*   **\"Glory of Love\" - Peter Cetera (1986):** From the movie \"The Karate Kid Part II\".\n*   **\"Hard to Say I'm Sorry\" - Chicago (1982):** Power Ballad.\n\n**90s and Beyond (Sometimes Blurring into Adult Contemporary Pop):**\n\n*   **\"Save the Best for Last\" - Vanessa Williams (1991):**  A sophisticated and elegant ballad.\n*   **\"Torn\" - Natalie Imbruglia (1997):**  A catchy and relatable song about heartbreak.\n*   **\"Kiss from a Rose\" - Seal (1994):**  Mysterious, romantic, and unforgettable.\n*   **\"You're Still the One\" - Shania Twain (1997):** A crossover hit that blends country and soft rock.\n*   **\"A Thousand Miles\" - Vanessa Carlton (2001):** Piano-driven and emotionally charged.\n*   **\"Hallelujah\" - Jeff Buckley (1994):** A cover, but this version has become so popular, it's now a modern standard.\n*   **\"Chasing Cars\" - Snow Patrol (2006):** A modern classic that builds into a powerful anthem.\n\n**Considerations for Defining Soft Rock:**\n\n*   **Instrumentation:**  Often features acoustic guitars, pianos, synthesizers, and string arrangements.\n*   **Vocals:**  Typically smooth, melodic, and often harmonically rich.\n*   **Lyrics:**  Common themes include love, relationships, nostalgia, and introspection.\n*   **Tempo:**  Generally slower to mid-tempo.\n*   **Emotional Tone:**  Melancholic, romantic, hopeful, or reflective.\n\nThis list is by no means exhaustive, but it provides a good starting point for exploring the vast and varied world of soft rock. Enjoy your listening!  You might also want to explore subgenres like yacht rock, which is a smoother, jazzier offshoot.\n",
